phase-3.log — Phase 3: Turn Loop & Loop Detection

=== Architect entry (2026-07-06) ===

Deliverable: docs/adr-phase-3-turn-loop.md

Decisions made:

1. Package layout: internal/loop/ with loop.go, halt.go, backoff.go, resume.go.
   No sub-packages. TurnLoop imports internal/llm, internal/tools, internal/store
   — never the reverse.

2. TurnLoop structure: Serial loop (model call → parse tool calls → dispatch
   each → halt check → repeat). Breaks when model returns text with no tool
   calls (HaltCompleted). Maximum 50 turns as backstop, cumulative token check
   (85% of context_max_tokens) as primary stop condition.

3. AgentConfig: Hand-constructed Go struct (Name, ModelName, BaseURL,
   ContextMaxTokens, Temperature, SystemPrompt, UserPrompt, Tools[AgentToolConfig]).
   Real YAML config parsing deferred to Phase 4.

4. Tool dispatch: Each tool call logged as two events (tool_call + tool_result).
   File-tracking tools (edit_file, create_file) also upsert a files row.
   Tool errors (especially ErrNoMatch, ErrAmbiguousMatch) formatted as clear
   model-facing messages, not crashes.

5. Hardcoded halt: file write_count > 5 triggers halt. Content hash comparison
   on consecutive edits detects unchanged-content rewrites as a stronger signal.
   Both checks run after every tool result with zero model call cost.

6. Delta/semantic halt: Every 5th turn, compact summary of recent events sent
   to the model with a narrow yes/no prompt. Uses the same model (not a separate
   cheap one — Phase 4+ optimization). Response parsed for "YES" prefix to trigger
   halt.

7. Cumulative token stop: cumulative_tokens > context_max_tokens * 0.85 checked
   before every LLM call. context_max_tokens is hand-constructed per agent config.
   This binds before max_turns in all normal cases.

8. Retry/backoff (all 6 error categories):

   - Timeout: exponential backoff (1s base, 2x multiplier, ±10% jitter),
     cumulative cap 5min, then halt triggers session-reuse
   - RateLimit: honor RetryAfter if present, else same backoff as Timeout
   - Quota: halt immediately, no retry, requires user intervention
   - Malformed: one immediate retry, then halt triggers session-reuse
   - Auth: halt immediately, no retry, requires user config fix
   - Unknown: bounded retry (max 3 attempts), then halt triggers session-reuse

9. Session-reuse sequence: On timeout/malformed/unknown halts, the same
   session_id is updated (resume_count incremented, started_at reset,
   ended_at cleared). A templated summary of prior files+events replaces
   the full message history. Template shape: "Previous attempt touched files
   X, Y; last failure was Z; halted due to ..."

10. ToolConfig.ProjectRoot symlink resolution (carried-forward from Phase 2):
    - NewDefaultRegistry updated to EvalSymlinks the project root at construction
    - TurnLoop stores the resolved root and constructs ToolConfig.ProjectRoot
      from it, so AllowPath's filepath.Rel operates on matching resolution bases
    - Option B chosen: pass resolvedRoot as a separate parameter to TurnLoop.New
      instead of extracting from registry via fragile type assertions

11. Content hash in tool results (carried-forward from Phase 2):
    - EditFileResult and CreateFileResult gain ContentHash string field
    - Both tools compute SHA-256 after successful write and populate the field
    - Loop passes the hash to store.UpsertFile for loop detection

12. Store changes: UpdateSession must also accept started_at and allow nil
    ended_at for session-reuse. RecentEventsBySession query with LIMIT added.

13. 4 new files, 5 modified files. Test strategy: unit tests per component
    using Fake LLM with Responder for multi-turn scenarios.

Key constraint carried forward: no config file parsing, no git integration,
no Phase 0 generator — those are Phases 4, 5, 6 respectively.

Flad to builder: Option B for root extraction; TestHelpers for multi-turn
Fake scenarios; store.UpdateSession expansion; verify write_count increments
on failed edits; content hash field addition to two tool result structs.

=== Librarian entry (2026-07-06) ===

Deliverable:
  specs/phase-3-loop-basics.feature  (16 scenarios)
  specs/phase-3-retry-and-resume.feature  (14 scenarios)

Coverage:

Area 1 — Loop basics (5 scenarios):
  - No tool calls -> HaltCompleted
  - Tool calls loop until model stops
  - Tool results appended to message history
  - Multiple tool calls processed serially
  - Tool errors surfaced as clear messages

Area 2 — Halt detection (8 scenarios):
  - Write-count threshold (hardcoded)
  - Content-hash unchanged halt (even below write count)
  - Content-hash first-write exemption
  - ErrNoMatch false-positive avoidance
  - Multiple halt conditions produce one event
  - Delta check triggers on loop signal
  - Delta check passes on progress
  - Delta check error does not halt

Area 3 — Token budget (3 scenarios):
  - Token stop before max_turns
  - Max-turns backstop
  - Exact boundary (no halt when under 85%)

Area 4 — Retry/backoff (10 scenarios):
  - Timeout -> backoff -> succeed
  - Timeout backoff exhaustion -> halt
  - RateLimit with RetryAfter header
  - RateLimit without RetryAfter -> exponential backoff
  - Quota -> halt immediately
  - Malformed -> retry once -> halt
  - Malformed -> retry once -> succeed
  - Auth -> halt immediately
  - Unknown -> retry 3x -> halt
  - Unknown -> recover before max

Area 5 — Session-reuse (3 scenarios):
  - resume_count incremented, same session_id
  - Resume summary is templated (not raw replay)
  - Summary reflects actual data (files, failure reason)

Area 6 — Retry-halt interaction (1 scenario):
  - Malformed retry does not count against write_counters

ADR ambiguities flagged to builder:

  1. $9.2 vs $9.6 (\"inline resume\" vs \"deferred resume\"):
     ADR $9.2 shows resumeSession updating DB inline within Run() and then
     returning the HaltReason. $9.6 describes buildInitialMessages checking
     resume_count on a SEPARATE Run() call. The scenarios assume the latter:
     resumeSession updates DB (resume_count++, cleared ended_at, new started_at)
     and Run() returns; caller calls Run() again which detects resume_count>0
     and builds a summary as the initial system message. Builder must resolve.

  2. ResumeCount on returned HaltReason:
     Scenarios assume resume_count reflects the INCREMENTED value (1 after the
     resume, not the original 0). If builder implements the other interpretation
     (HaltReason shows pre-increment value), these assertions will need updating.

  3. Backoff timing in tests:
     \"approximately 1s\" / \"approximately 2s\" assertions assume a mockable
     BackoffStrategy interface or a Fake clock. Without it, ~30s RetryAfter
     assertions make tests unacceptably slow. Builder should inject a
     strategies.Backoff or use a clock abstraction.

  4. Delta check LLM:
     ADR says same model is used. Scenarios assume a SEPARATE Fake for the
     delta check is overridable (e.g., via a TurnLoop config field). If builder
     uses the same LLM client, the test setup must distinguish per-role responses.
     This is an Open Decision in the ADR; scenarios assume overrideable.

  5. Pre-populated DB for resume scenarios:
     \"Resume summary reflects actual session data\" uses opaque Given steps
     (e.g., \"first session attempt made 3 edits to main.go\"). Builder must
     decide: pre-populate the Store directly, or run a full 3-turn session?
     Pre-population is cleaner and faster. Scenarios are compatible with either.

Build instructions:
  - Implement internal/loop/ from specs/phase-3-loop-basics.feature first
    (no retry, no resume -- pure loop + halt + tokens)
  - Then implement specs/phase-3-retry-and-resume.feature
    (retry/backoff, session-reuse, retry-halt interaction)
  - \"approximately Ns\" assertions in tests: use a mock clock or
    BackoffStrategy interface; do NOT use time.Sleep in unit tests

Spec validated. Ready for Builder.
